{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17475968","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17475968"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:39:24+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:39:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13020"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13020","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13020"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.11,0.04,0.46,0.27]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5457"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114079"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5457","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5457"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question","status":"accepted","createdAt":"2023-06-10T13:38:51+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-15T08:52:37+09:30","updatedAction":"revised","acceptedAt":"2024-01-10T14:44:23+10:30","editorNotifiedAt":null,"feedbackAt":"2025-09-16 08:28:47"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13020"}},"updatedBy":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"7912"}},"author":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"6927"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96094"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"476"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1254"},{"type":"tags","id":"2545"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4965"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9259"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10357"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10378"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16658"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42838"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44143"}]},"lastContribution":{"data":null},"lastRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96094"}},"lastActivity":{"data":null},"lastFeedback":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114079","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114079"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 11-year-old child presents with a one week history of high fevers and more recent onset of a generalised, erythematous, maculopapular rash on his arms and legs. He had seen his General Practitioner eight days ago with only a sore throat and had been prescribed empiric amoxicillin after a bacterial swab was sent for culture. He has been taking this for the last six days.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, his blood pressure is 105/68 mmHg, pulse 100/min and temperature 38.7\u00b0C. He has pharyngitis and enlargement of his cervical lymph nodes, and mild splenomegaly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA complete blood count shows a lymphocytosis, with approximately 20% of the lymphocytes demonstrating an atypical appearance.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Stevens-Johnson syndrome","Measles","Varicella zoster","Drug-induced rash","Kawasaki disease"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis scenario is consistent with infectious mononucleosis caused by Epstein-Barr virus. This often presents fevers, pharyngitis and generalised lymphadenopathy, as well as splenomegaly. It is also consistent with lymphocytosis, and atypical lymphocytes on a peripheral blood smear. In children infected with Epstein-Barr virus, there is a high incidence of developing a generalised maculopapular, erythematous rash affecting the extremities when treated with amoxicillin (\u003Cstrong\u003Edrug-induced rash\u003C/strong\u003E).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMeasles\u003C/strong\u003E is a highly contagious viral infection caused by the measles virus which typically presents with the 3C\u0027s of cough, coryza, and conjunctivitis. The rash in measles is maculopapular and spreads from the face down to the trunk and the remaining parts of the body. The rash in measles typically presents a few days after the prodromal symptoms, at the peak of the fever. The description of the rash along with the presence of pharyngitis, generalized lymphadenopathy, and splenomegaly makes measles an unlikely option.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVaricella zoster (VZV)\u003C/strong\u003E causes chickenpox, a highly contagious viral infection characterised by an itchy generalised vesicular rash of fluid filled blisters or crusts/scabs. Chickenpox is often associated with mild systemic symptoms of fever, malaise and loss of appetite. The rash usually starts on the face and trunk before spreading to other parts of the body. The character of the rash described in the clinical scenario does not fit a picture of VZV, hence this option is unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStevens-Johnson Syndrome (SJS\u003C/strong\u003E) is a severe and rare disorder characterised by a widespread rash with blistering and involvement of mucous membranes. This syndrome is often triggered by medications, mainly antiepileptics and antibiotics, which typically present with flu-like symptoms and are followed by an acute onset of painful, erythematous rash which can progress to involve mucous membranes of the eyes, mouth, and genitals. The scenario describes the child with a generalised maculopapular rash primarily in the extremities, which does not align with the typical presentation of SJS.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EKawasaki disease\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003E(KD)\u003C/strong\u003E can present with prolonged fever, cervical lymphadenopathy and generalised polymorphous rash. However, KD usually presents in children younger than 5 years old. In addition, patients usually present with mucosal changes and non-suppurative conjunctivitis. This patient does not fulfill the clinical diagnostic criteria of KD.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Use of amoxicillin is associated with the development of a generalised maculopapular rash in patient with infectious mononucleosis."],"references":["Thompson DF, Ramos CL. Antibiotic-Induced Rash in Patients With Infectious Mononucleosis. Ann Pharmacother. 2017 Feb;51(2):154-162. doi: 10.1177/1060028016669525. Epub 2016 Oct 1. PMID: 27620494.","Morishita KA, Goldman RD. Kawasaki disease recognition and treatment. Canadian Family Physician. 2020 Aug 1;66(8):577-9."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96094"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13020"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96094","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96094"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-15T08:52:37+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-15T08:52:37+09:30","number":10,"notes":"typo corrected in stem - can\u0027t find in answer explanation","plagiarismCheckedAt":null,"plagiarismScore":null,"plagiarismReportUrl":null},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5457"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114079"}},"author":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"7912"}},"generation":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags",